I&#x27;ll take your money.<p>First, a change because the optimizer will pre-compute the sum:<p><pre><code>  #include <stdio.h>
  #include <stdlib.h>

  int main (int argc, char *argv[])
  {
    long a, bound=10000000;
    long sum = 0;
    if (argc > 1) {
      bound = atoi(argv[1]);
    }
    /* for loop execution */
    for( a = 0; a < bound; a++ ) {
      sum += a;
    }
    printf(&quot;sum: %lu
&quot;, sum);
    return 0;
  }
</code></pre>
I&#x27;ll time the performance across a range of values.<p><pre><code>  % cc tmp.c && time ./a.out 1000000
  sum: 499999500000
  0.005u 0.000s 0:00.00 0.0%	0+0k 0+0io 1pf+0w
  % cc tmp.c && time ./a.out 10000000
  sum: 49999995000000
  0.030u 0.000s 0:00.03 100.0%	0+0k 0+0io 1pf+0w
  % cc tmp.c && time ./a.out 100000000
  sum: 4999999950000000
  0.303u 0.000s 0:00.33 90.9%	0+0k 0+0io 1pf+0w
</code></pre>
You&#x27;ll notice that my timings for 10000000, at 0.03 seconds, was comparable to the timings in the essay.<p>If the printf overhead were the dominate cost then we would expect to see less variance in the timing. Instead, we see there&#x27;s a linear increase, which is exactly what we expect if the loop is the primary cost.<p>So no, most of the time is not spent in printing the result.<p>I&#x27;ll also test with optimizations enabled:<p><pre><code>  % cc -O3 tmp.c && time ./a.out 1000000
  sum: 499999500000
  0.000u 0.000s 0:00.00 0.0%	0+0k 0+0io 1pf+0w
  % cc -O3 tmp.c && time ./a.out 10000000
  sum: 49999995000000
  0.000u 0.001s 0:00.00 0.0%	0+0k 0+0io 1pf+0w
  % cc -O3 tmp.c && time ./a.out 100000000
  sum: 4999999950000000
  0.000u 0.000s 0:00.00 0.0%	0+0k 0+0io 1pf+0w
  % cc -O3 tmp.c && time ./a.out 1000000000
  sum: 499999999500000000
  0.000u 0.000s 0:00.00 0.0%	0+0k 0+0io 1pf+0w
</code></pre>
The optimizer does pretty well on this code.
